source-type:description.@value: chemistry treatment in an atmospheric model that calculates atmospheric oxidant concentrations (including at least ozone), rather than prescribing them
radiation component of an atmospheric model run 'offline'
coupled atmosphere-ocean global climate model, additionally including explicit representation of at least the land and sea ice
aerosol treatment in an atmospheric model where concentrations are calculated based on emissions, transformation, and removal processes (rather than being prescribed or omitted entirely)
ocean general circulation model run uncoupled from an AGCM but, usually including a sea-ice model
atmospheric general circulation model run with prescribed ocean surface conditions and usually a model of the land surface
slab-ocean used with an AGCM in representing the atmosphere-ocean coupled system
land model run uncoupled from the atmosphere
biogeochemistry model component that at the very least accounts for carbon reservoirs and fluxes in the atmosphere, terrestrial biosphere, and ocean

product:description.@value: Data collected from direct measurements of the climate system. This includes data from ground stations, satellites, buoys, and other observational platforms, which serve as a reference for validating and comparing model outputs.

Output produced from a model simulation. This includes the various data points and metrics generated as a result of running climate models, which simulate physical, chemical, and biological processes affecting the climate system.

Data that has been processed or transformed from raw model output. Derived data includes value-added products such as anomalies, indices, or other statistics that are computed from the original model outputs.
Data sets used to drive model simulations. These include external factors like greenhouse gas concentrations, solar radiation, and land use changes that influence the climate model outputs.
